ps and two papillary muscles"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe tricuspid valve contains \u003Cstrong\u003Ethree cusps and three papillary muscles\u003C/strong\u003E. The cusps are the anterior, posterior and septal leaflets. These cusps are anchored by fibrous cords called chordae tendineae, which connect to papillary muscles projecting from the right ventricular wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis anatomical arrangement ensures unidirectional blood flow by preventing backflow from the right ventricle to the right atrium during ventricular contraction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The tricuspid valve consists of anterior, posterior and septal cusps that prevent backflow of blood from the right ventricle to right atrium.","Chordae tendineae connect each cusp to papillary muscles in the right ventricle.","The three papillary muscles contract during systole to maintain valve position and prevent prolapse."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64803"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18500"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64803"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T20:00:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T20:01:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11229"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79480"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"ite